(94, 134291, 'Sao Paulo', 1930, 'Soccer', 'Brazilian Brasileirao', '4351', 'Muricy Ramalho', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/stadium/wvrrxs1420419616.jpg', 'The EstÃ¡dio CÃ­cero Pompeu de Toledo, widely known as Morumbi (Brazilian Portuguese: ), is a football stadium located in the Morumbi district in SÃ£o Paulo, Brazil. It is the home of SÃ£o Paulo Futebol Clube and its formal name honors CÃ­cero Pompeu de Toledo, who was SÃ£o Paulo Futebol Clubes chairman during most of the stadium construction and died before its inauguration. Morumbi is the largest privately owned stadium in Brazil. The stadium was designed by the architect JoÃ£o Batista Vilanova Artigas.\r\nIn the early years of its existence, SÃ£o Paulo Futebol Clube used for their headquarters and home field the ChÃ¡cara da Floresta, located beside the Ponte das Bandeiras next to the TietÃª river in the center of SÃ£o Paulo. For this reason, the first incarnation of the club, that existed from 1930 to 1935, is referred to as "SÃ£o Paulo da Floresta".\r\n\r\nWhen the club was refounded in December 1935, since the ChÃ¡cara da Floresta now belonged to Clube de Regatas TietÃª, which had absorbed the original SÃ£o Paulo Futebol Clube, the refounded SÃ£o Paulo didnt have its own field. From 1936, it began to rent the AntÃ´nio Alonso stadium, which then belonged to Clube AtlÃ©tico Paulista. In 1938, after merging with Estudantes Paulista (originated in 1937 by the merger of Estudantes de SÃ£o Paulo and Paulista) SÃ£o Paulo acquired the AntÃ´nio Alonso. When the EstÃ¡dio do Pacaembu was inaugurated in 1940, SÃ£o Paulo began to use it as a home field. the AntÃ´nio Alonso stadium was sold to Juventus in 1942.\r\n\r\nIn 1944, SÃ£o Paulo bought a piece of ground called CanindÃ©, which was only used as a headquarters and training location. The area was too small for the construction of a large stadium, so studies were done to find another home within the city of SÃ£o Paulo.\r\n\r\nIn 1952, SÃ£o Paulos chairman CÃ­cero Pompeu de Toledo requested from the citys mayor, Armando de Arruda Pereira, a groundplot in the Ibirapuera neighborhood. The mayor refused the request, but donated a groundplot in the Morumbi neighborhood to SÃ£o Paulo.', 'SÃ£o Paulo', 'www.saopaulofc.net', '', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/xptvsu1420407458.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/uwuprq1423783034.png', ''),
(95, 134463, 'Sport', 1905, 'Soccer', 'Brazilian Brasileirao', '4351', '', '', '', '', 'EstÃ¡dio Adelmar da Costa Carvalho, usually known as EstÃ¡dio Ilha do Retiro or simply Ilha do Retiro, is a sports stadium situated in Recife, in the Brazilian state of Pernambuco, owned by Sport Recife.\r\n\r\nThe stadiums official name is EstÃ¡dio Adelmar da Costa Carvalho, and it was inaugurated on July 4, 1937. The stadiums common name, Ilha do Retiro, is the name of the neighborhood where it is located. The stadiums official name, Adelmar da Costa Carvalho, is in honor of the Sport Recife president who presided over the first major renovation of the stadium. Blocks of high-rise flats border the ground giving the residents and visitors excellent views of the games in the stadium from their windows and balconies.', 'Recife', 'www.sportrecife.com.br', '', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/wpttqr1422410173.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/yttqst1423783099.png', ''),
