(496, 134010, 'Lech Poznan', 1922, 'Soccer', 'Polish Ekstraklasa', '4422', 'Jan Urban', '', '', '', 'The Municipal Stadium in PoznaÅ„ (Polish: Stadion Miejski w Poznaniu, pronounced ), sometimes called BuÅ‚garska Street Stadium or INEA Stadion  for sponsorship reasons, is an association football stadium in PoznaÅ„, Poland. It has a league capacity of 43,269 (all seated). The stadium was originally built between 1968 and 1980. From its inauguration in August 1980, Lech PoznaÅ„ has used the ground as its main venue. Since 2010 it has also been used by Warta PoznaÅ„. The ground is situated on the street ul. BuÅ‚garska in the southwestern part of the city (Grunwald district).\r\n\r\nIn the years 2003â€“2010, the stadium underwent a complete reconstruction, including the building of four new fully covered stands. Currently it is the fifth-largest stadium in Poland (after National Stadium, Silesia Stadium, The Municipal Stadium in Wroclaw and PGE Arena GdaÅ„sk) and third largest in Ekstraklasa (after the latter two). The grand opening after final renovation took place on 20 September 2010, with Stings Symphonicity Tour concert.', 'PoznaÅ„', 'www.lechpoznan.pl', 'www.facebook.com/lechpoznan.oficjalna', 'twitter.com/lechpoznan', 'instagram.com/lechpoznan1922', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/tvstpp1448218832.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/qvsxux1423836683.png', ''),
(497, 135299, 'Lechia GdaÅ„sk', 1945, 'Soccer', 'Polish Ekstraklasa', '4422', 'Thomas von Heesen', '', '', '', 'The Stadion Energa GdaÅ„sk (Polish pronunciation: ), previously called the Baltic Arena and PGE Arena GdaÅ„sk, is a football stadium in GdaÅ„sk, Poland. It is used mostly for football matches and is the home stadium of Lechia GdaÅ„sk currently playing in the Ekstraklasa. The Stadium is located on ul. PokoleÅ„ Lechii GdaÅ„sk ("Generations of Lechia GdaÅ„sk street") in the northern part of the city (Letnica district). The capacity of the stands is 43,615 spectators, all seated and roofed. The stadium is the largest arena in Ekstraklasa and the third largest in the country (after National Stadium and Silesia Stadium).\r\n\r\nConstruction of the stadium started in 2008 and was completed mid-2011. The opening match was between Lechia GdaÅ„sk and Cracovia and ended with 1â€“1 draw. The first international match, Poland - Germany, took place on 6 September 2011 and ended 2-2. The match was relocated from Warsaw because the National Stadium was not ready. It is used by Lechia GdaÅ„sk since the White-and-Green relocated there from MOSiR Stadium.\r\n\r\nThe stadium was also one of the designated venues for the finals of Euro 2012. It hosted four matches during the tournament. Three matches in Group C and one quarterfinal were played there.\r\n\r\nSince 2010 the official name of the stadium was PGE Arena GdaÅ„sk on the basis of a sponsorship agreement with Polska Grupa Energetyczna (PGE Group). The contract ended, however, on 31 September 2015, after PGE chose not to renew the contract. On the 9th November Energa was revealed as the new stadiums sponsor.', 'GdaÅ„sk', 'www.lechia.pl/index.php', 'www.facebook.com/LechiaGdansk', 'twitter.com/LechiaGdanskSA', 'instagram.com/lechia_gdansk', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/swrtpv1448218940.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/qvtxwt1423836782.png', ''),
