(650, 133835, 'Konyaspor', 1981, 'Soccer', 'Turkish SÃ¼per Lig', '4339', 'Aykut Kocaman', '', '', '', 'Torku Arena is a multi-purpose stadium in Konya, Turkey. It is primarily used for football matches of Konyaspor. It is part of complex of sports venues that are planned on the outskirts of the city, as part of the Konya Olympic Village. It replaced the aging Konya AtatÃ¼rk Stadium, which has been in use since the early 1950s. The stadium has a capacity of nearly 42.276 people (all-seated) and is totally covered.\r\n\r\nThe stadium is located in SelÃ§uklu, the main district of Konya.', 'Konya', 'www.konyaspor.org.tr', 'www.facebook.com/Konyaspor', 'twitter.com/KonyasporSK', 'instagram.com/konyasporresmi', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/rxwptr1448203413.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/tqtwux1423793542.png', ''),
(651, 133792, 'Mersin Idman Yurdu', 1925, 'Soccer', 'Turkish SÃ¼per Lig', '4339', 'BÃ¼lent Korkmaz', '', '', '', 'Mersin Arena, is a multi-purpose stadium in Mersin, Turkey. Completed in 2013, it is the new home ground for SÃ¼per Lig club Mersin Ä°dmanyurdu SK replacing the old Tevfik SÄ±rrÄ± GÃ¼r Stadium. It hosted the opening and closing ceremonies for the 2013 Mediterranean Games. The all-seater stadium has the capacity to host 25,534 spectators during football games.  It is also a common known fact that it was built on a cemetery from 1748.', 'Mersin', 'www.mersinidmanyurdu.com.tr', 'www.facebook.com/miyofficial', 'twitter.com/miy_official33', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/qyqpwv1448203732.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/vwqyrp1423793642.png', ''),
(652, 133885, 'Rizespor', 1953, 'Soccer', 'Turkish SÃ¼per Lig', '4339', 'Hikmet Karaman', '', '', '', 'Yeni Rize Åžehir StadÄ± is a multi-use stadium in Rize, Turkey. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of Ã‡aykur Rizespor. The stadium has a capacity of 15,197 spectators and it opened in 2009. It replaced Rize AtatÃ¼rk Stadium as the home of Ã‡aykur Rizespor.', 'Rize', 'www.caykurrizespor.org.tr', 'www.facebook', 'twitter.com/CRizesporAS', 'www.instagram.com/crizesporas', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/qttsry1448203856.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/qrsrvs1423794648.png', ''),
(653, 133806, 'Sivasspor', 1967, 'Soccer', 'Turkish SÃ¼per Lig', '4339', 'Okan Buruk', '', '', '', 'Sivas 4 EylÃ¼l Stadium (Turkish: Sivas 4 EylÃ¼l Stadyumu) is a multi-purpose stadium in Sivas, Turkey. It is currently used mostly for football matches and is the home ground of Sivasspor. The stadium holds 14,998 people.\r\n\r\nIn 2006 the stadium was renovated with extra 1,200 seats and was initially painted red and white.\r\n\r\nInitially it has been a rumour that if Sivasspor joins the UEFA Champions League or the UEFA Cup next season they will move into the New 4 EylÃ¼l Stadium which is a 25,000 all seated stadium.', 'Sivas', 'www.sivasspor.org.tr', 'www.facebook.com/sivasspor', 'www.twitter.com/sivassporkulubu', 'instagram.com/sivassporsk', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/qxxsxu1448204098.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/wtsqyt1423793771.png', ''),
(654, 133796, 'Trabzonspor', 1967, 'Soccer', 'Turkish SÃ¼per Lig', '4339', 'Sadi TekelioÄŸlu', '', '', '', 'HÃ¼seyin Avni Aker Stadium (Turkish: HÃ¼seyin Avni Aker Stadyumu) is the home ground of the Turkish football (soccer) club Trabzonspor. The stadium was built in 1951 with a capacity of 2,500 seats. After several renovations, the capacity was increased to 20,750 in 2008. The stadium is named after HÃ¼seyin Avni Aker, a teacher and regional administrator for education, who served during 1940â€“1944 in Trabzon and contributed much to the local sports. It will be replaced by the new stadium (41.513 seats) currently being built in AkyazÄ±.', 'Trabzon', 'www.trabzonspor.org.tr', 'www.facebook.com/Trabzonspor', 'twitter.com/#!/trabzonspor', 'instagram.com/trabzonspor', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/rrsrvv1448204214.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/wyuwpy1423793554.png', ''),
(655, 134392, 'Ch. Odessa', 1936, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Oleksandr Babych', '', '', '', 'Chernomorets Stadium is a football stadium built in 2011 in Odesa, Ukraine. The stadium has a capacity of 34,164 and is the home of FC Chornomorets Odesa. The inaugural match, between FC Chornomorets Odesa and FC Karpaty Lviv, was played on November 19, 2011, and ended with a 2â€“2 draw. The first goal was scored by Vitaliy Balashov in the 46th minute from penalty.\r\n\r\nThe stadium was constructed on the site of the old Soviet multi-use Central Stadium of the Black Sea Shipping Company (ChMP), which was demolished in 2009.\r\n\r\nThe venue was considered to be one of the stadiums of EURO 2012 but failed to be nominated as such', 'Odesa', 'chernomorets.odessa.ua', 'www.facebook.com/pages/Ð¤ÑƒÑ‚Ð±Ð¾Ð»ÑŒÐ½Ñ‹Ð¹-ÐšÐ»ÑƒÐ±-Ð§ÐµÑ€Ð½Ð¾Ð¼Ð¾Ñ€ÐµÑ†-ÐžÐ´ÐµÑÑÐ°/167064326743159?v=wall', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/uvvsyw1447696161.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/wtpytr1423788061.png', ''),
(656, 134119, 'Dnipro', 1918, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Myron Markevych', '', '', '', 'Dnipro-Arena is a football stadium in Dnipropetrovsk, Ukraine. It is mostly for football matches and hosts the homes matches of FC Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk. The stadium has a capacity of 31,003 people. It replaced Dnipros old Soviet Metalurh Stadium.\r\n\r\nIt staged the 2010 FIFA World Cup qualifying match between Ukraine and England as the Olimpiysky National Sports Complex in Kiev was being rebuilt ready for UEFA Euro 2012. The Dnipro-Arena was chosen as a possible venue for UEFA Euro 2012, but was dropped from the list in May 2009. The capacity fell short of the minimum 33,000 seats required by UEFA.', 'Dnipropetrovsk', 'www.fcdnipro.ua', 'www.facebook.com/fcdniproua', 'twitter.com/fcdnipro', 'instagram.com/fcdnipro', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/typwxs1447696311.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/vpxpyp1423788113.png', ''),
(657, 133944, 'Dynamo Kiev', 1927, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Serhiy Rebrov', '', '', '', 'The Olympic National Sports Complex (also known as Olympic Stadium; Ukrainian: ÐÐ°Ñ†Ñ–Ð¾Ð½Ð°Ð»ÑŒÐ½Ð¸Ð¹ ÑÐ¿Ð¾Ñ€Ñ‚Ð¸Ð²Ð½Ð¸Ð¹ ÐºÐ¾Ð¼Ð¿Ð»ÐµÐºÑ "ÐžÐ»Ñ–Ð¼Ð¿Ñ–Ð¹ÑÑŒÐºÐ¸Ð¹") is a multi-use sports and recreation facility in Kyiv, Ukraine, located on the slopes of the citys central Cherepanov Hill, Pechersk Raion. The stadium is the premier sports venue in Ukraine and the second largest in Eastern Europe after Moscows Luzhniki Stadium. The complex beside its stadium also features several other sports facilities and is designed to host the Olympic Games (the stadium hosted some football matches at the 1980 Summer Olympics).\r\n\r\nFollowing extensive renovation works, including the construction of a new roof, the stadium was reopened on 9 October 2011 with a performance by Shakira and had its international inauguration with a 3â€“3 friendly draw by Ukraine against Germany on 11 November 2011. It hosted the final of Euro 2012.', 'Kyiv, Ukraine', 'www.fcdynamo.kiev.ua', 'facebook.com/fcdynamoua', 'twitter.com/dynamokyiv', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/stxrpx1447696362.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/xywtqu1423788158.png', ''),
(658, 134122, 'FC Metalist Kharkiv', 1925, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Oleksandr Sevidov', '', '', '', '"Metalist" Oblast Sports Complex (Ukrainian: ÐžÐ±Ð»Ð°ÑÐ½Ð¸Ð¹ ÑÐ¿Ð¾Ñ€Ñ‚Ð¸Ð²Ð½Ð¸Ð¹ ÐºÐ¾Ð¼Ð¿Ð»ÐµÐºÑ Â«ÐœÐµÑ‚Ð°Ð»Ñ–ÑÑ‚Â»), commonly known as Metalist Stadium (Ukrainian: Ð¡Ñ‚Ð°Ð´Ñ–Ð¾Ð½ Â«ÐœÐµÑ‚Ð°Ð»Ñ–ÑÑ‚Â»), is a multi-use stadium in Kharkiv, Ukraine. It is currently used chiefly for football matches and is the home of FC Metalist Kharkiv. The stadium, which was a venue for Euro 2012, currently seats 40,003.', 'Kharkiv', 'www.metalist.ua', 'www.facebook.com/MetalistFC', 'twitter.com/fcmetalist', 'instagram.com/fcmetalist', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/ysvxuv1447696684.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/wqvwwr1423788188.png', ''),
(659, 135483, 'FC Olexandria', 1948, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Volodymyr Sharan', '', '', '', 'Cultural Sports Complex Nika Stadium is a football stadium in the city of Oleksandria, Ukraine.\r\n\r\nThe stadium has a capacity of 7,000 spectators.\r\n\r\nThe stadium is the home ground of Ukrainian Premier League club PFC Oleksandria.\r\n\r\nBetween 2004â€“2006 MFK Oleksandria played their home games also at the stadium.\r\n\r\nSeventy percent of the seating is under cover. The main stadium has administration offices as well as a conference hall.', 'Oleksandriya, Kirovohrad Oblast', 'fco.com.ua', 'www.facebook.com/fcalexandria', 'twitter.com/fco1948', 'instagram.com/fcolexandria', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/vsqryx1447695405.png', '', ''),
(660, 134425, 'Hoverla Uzhhorod', 1925, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Vyacheslav Hroznyi', '', '', '', 'Avanhard Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Uzhhorod, Ukraine. It is currently used mostly for football matches, and is the home of FC Hoverla Uzhhorod. The stadium holds 12,000 people.\r\nThe stadium was built in 1952 and renovated in 2005. The size of the field is 104X68 m. The architects were Yevhen Valts, Emil Egresi, Sandor Kavac. Currently the stadium is owned primarily by the municipal government. In 2012 the stadium was leased to the best regional football club FC Hoverla Uzhhorod for the next 20 years.', 'Uzhorod ', 'fcgoverla.uz.ua', '', 'twitter.com/FCGoverla', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/xyrwtu1421793240.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/swxvqs1423788074.png', ''),
(661, 134426, 'Karpaty', 1963, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Igor JoviÄ‡eviÄ‡', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/stadium/svtypw1421791334.jpg', 'Ukraina Stadium (Ukrainian: ÑÑ‚Ð°Ð´Ñ–Ð¾Ð½ Ð£ÐºÑ€Ð°Ñ—Ð½Ð°) is a multi-purpose stadium in Lviv, Ukraine. It is currently used mostly for football matches, and was the home of FC Karpaty Lviv. "Ukraina" is also an alternative stadium for the Ukraine national football team where it played several of its qualification games for various tournaments. The stadium is located in the central part of the city in the Snopkiv Park which is classified as the monument of park architecture (landscape art).\r\n\r\nThe stadium was erected in three years by the method of public construction (collective construction), meaning that each big company of Lviv was responsible for construction of its own part of the future stadium. The construction was headed by the third secretary of the Communist Party City Committee, Vasyl Mazur, who also took part in the construction. The architects were Yaroslav Nazarkevych, Larysa Skoryk, Yaroslav Porokhnavets, Volodymyr Blyusyuk. The official debut game took place on August 18, 1963 when the local Karpaty Lviv were playing against the visiting Zalgiris Vilnius. On the 86th minute Ivan Dykovets failed to convert a penalty kick and the game ended in the loss by the home team, 0:1.\r\n\r\nIn its initial years the Druzhba Stadium had capacity to hold 41,700 seated spectators. The most attended games were an exhibition game with Palmeiras (Brazil) on May 26, 1970 (around 50,000) and the game with Dynamo Kyiv on June 27, 1971 as part of the 1971 Soviet Top League season (51,000). On October 13, 1971 the Soviet Union Olympic football team was hosting its opponents from Austria in a qualification game for the 1972 Summer Olympics.\r\n\r\nIn 1990 by the initiative of the president of Karpaty Lviv, Karlo Miklyosh (former member of Ukraina Lwow), the name of stadium was changed to "Ukraina". In 1999 the stadium was renovated in preparation to the Karpatys participation in the 1999â€“2000 UEFA Cup, after which the stadiums capacity was reduced to 28,051. In 2007 a new grass pitch was installed at the stadium. Ukraina also has four floodlight towers with lighting power of 1,200 lux.', 'Lviv', 'www.fckarpaty.lviv.ua', 'www.facebook.com/fckarpaty', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/rsptsu1447696881.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/xvsuty1423788170.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/logo/rywrsr1421790983.png'),
(662, 134429, 'Met. Zaporizhzhia', 1935, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Anatoliy Chantsev', '', '', '', 'Slavutych Arena is a football-only stadium in Zaporizhia, Ukraine. After major renovations, it was reopened once again in July 2006. Before 2006 the stadium carried name Central Stadium Metalurh (or Metalurh Stadium).\r\nIt is used for football matches and is the home of Metalurh Zaporizhia. The stadiums official maximum capacity is 12,000.\r\nIn 2001 Football Federation of Ukraine suspended the stadium and Metalurh played its home games at the AvtoZAZ Stadium which was a home ground of FC Torpedo Zaporizhia. After the renovations Metalurh returned home.', 'Zaporizhia', 'www.fcmetalurg.com', 'www.facebook.com/fcmetallurgzp/', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/wvqwpv1421792723.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/vwsquv1423788242.png', ''),
(663, 134591, 'Olimpik Donetsk', 2001, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Roman Sanzhar', '', '', '', 'Sports Complex Olimpik is a football stadium in the city of Donetsk, Ukraine.\r\n\r\nOriginally when the complex was built the stadium had seating for 680 spectators. Later in the autumn of 2010 it was expanded to 1000 spectators. Major reconstruction occurred both in 2013 and 2014 with the addition of 2 small stands and currently there is room for 3,000 spectators.\r\n\r\nThe stadium is located on the territory of 7.4 ha (18 acres) in one of the oldest areas of Donetsk known as Bosse.\r\n\r\nThe stadium facilities include four locker rooms, two coaching rooms, a referees room, a medical center, a media press area seating for 35â€“40, a gymnasium on the ground floor and separate rooms for players with dining facilities on the second floor. There is also reserved parking at the ground.', 'Donetsk', 'olimpik.com.ua', 'www.facebook.com/fcolimpik', 'twitter.com/fcolimpik', 'instagram.com/fcolimpik', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/vwtvqr1421787901.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/wsqxrs1423788134.png', ''),
(664, 134126, 'Shakhtar Donetsk', 1936, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Mircea Lucescu', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/stadium/xrtvsp1420413092.jpg', 'Donbass Arena or Donbas Arena (Ukrainian: Ð”Ð¾Ð½Ð±Ð°ÌÑ ÐÑ€ÐµÌÐ½Ð° , Russian: Ð”Ð¾Ð½Ð±Ð°ÌÑc ÐÑ€ÐµÌÐ½Ð°) is a stadium with a natural grass pitch in Donetsk, Ukraine that opened on 29 August 2009. The facility is located in the center of the city, in the Lenin Comsomol park. With a capacity of 52,518 spectators, the stadium hosts FC Shakhtar Donetsk matches and hosted some matches of Euro 2012. It is also one of the popular nightlife spots in Donetsk.\r\n\r\nThe initial estimated cost of the project was $250 million. $30M has been allocated to set up a recreational park around the stadium. The final cost of the project will reach $400M.\r\n\r\nThe name of the stadium represents the shortened name for the Donets basin industrial region, hence - Donbas, however the official name in English spells after the Russian orthography.', 'Donetsk, Ukraine', 'www.shakhtar.com/ua', 'www.facebook.com/fcshakhtar', 'twitter.com/FCShakhtar', 'instagram.com/fcshakhtar', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/sqrxsr1421791799.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/vttwry1423788179.png', ''),
(665, 135484, 'Stal Dneprodzhezhinsk', 1926, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Volodymyr Mazyar', '', '', '', 'Metalurh Stadium is a football-only stadium in Dniprodzerzhynsk, Ukraine. It is currently used for football matches, and is the home of Stal Dniprodzerzhynsk. The stadiums official maximum capacity is 2,900.\r\n\r\nThe stadium was built 1933 and was called "Metalurh". However at times the stadium was called different names such as "Playground Palace of Culture" and "Stal Stadium".\r\n\r\nIn 2003 the stadium was reconstructed. Heating was installed so that the pitch would not freeze. Also were installed new plastic seats, an irrigation system and an electronic scoreboard.', 'Dniprodzerzhynsk, Dnipropetrovsk Oblast', '', '', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/ruyypv1447695945.png', '', ''),
(666, 134423, 'Volyn', 1960, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Vitaliy Kvartsyanyi', '', '', '', 'Avanhard Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Lutsk, Ukraine. It is currently used mostly for football matches, and is the home of FC Volyn Lutsk. The stadium holds 12,080 people and opened in 1960.', 'Lutsk', 'www.fcvolyn.net', 'www.facebook.com/FCVolynLutsk', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/wvpyqp1447697193.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/rxrpts1423788213.png', ''),
(667, 134428, 'Vorskla', 1955, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Vasyl Sachko', '', '', '', 'Oleksiy Butovsky Vorskla Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Poltava, Ukraine. It is currently used mostly for football matches, and is the home of FC Vorskla Poltava. The stadium holds 24,795 people. It was built in 1974 and has undergone several reconstructions after, most notably in 2000, when the facade of the stadium was renovated. In 2008, the most notable feature of the restoration was the installation of a coloured screen. The renovation was done for Ukrainian Super Cup, which was played at the stadium. The cup has traveled outside of Odessa for the first time due to renovation works at Chornomorets Stadium, the annual venue for the title game.', 'Poltava', 'www.vorskla.com.ua', 'www.facebook.com/fcvorskla', 'twitter.com/vorsklacomua', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/vqxqyw1447699914.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/tyqypy1423788096.png', ''),
(668, 134422, 'Zorya', 1923, 'Soccer', 'Ukrainian Premier League', '4354', 'Yuriy Vernydub', '', '', '', 'Avanhard Stadium is a multi-purpose stadium in Luhansk, Ukraine. The stadium holds 22,288 people.\r\n\r\nThe stadium was built in 1951 as the Kliment Voroshilov Stadium. In 1957 the stadiums capacity was 7,447. It was not until 1961 when it was renamed into Avanhard Stadium. In 1967 the Avanhard Stadium could hold 40,000 spectators. In 1974 there were installed running tracks. In 1986 due to modernization, the stadiums capacity was reduced to 32,243. In 2002 the stadium ownership has changed when it was transferred from Luhanskteplovoz to the Luhansk Oblast Administration. In 2003 there were conducted major renovations to the stadiums facilities, because of that its capacity was reduced to 22,288. In 2011 there was replaced the turf, installed drainage and heat systems.', 'Luhansk', 'zarya-lugansk.com', 'www.facebook.com/FCZoryaLuhansk', '', '', '', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/badge/vrqtvv1447700054.png', 'http://www.thesportsdb.com/images/media/team/jersey/xsqsuy1423788144.png', ''),
